20/5/2019

Background

  • Populations change through three processes: mortality, fertility, and migration.

  • Changes in mortality contribute considerably to population dynamics and variation in the levels of mortality lead to changes in the age distribution of the population.

  • This has repercussions on almost all areas of a society, including its health-care system, health and life insurance, as well as pension schemes.

  • Demographic research investigates levels and trends of mortality, fertility and migration processes and develops numerous techniques to measure and analyze them

Outline

  • The first part reviews traditional and well-established models in mortality analysis.

  • The fundamental Poisson assumption for the total number of deaths over a specified age- and year-interval will be introduced.

  • Simple models for portraying mortality over age, and more sophisticated approaches for modeling mortality over both age and times will be reviewed in detail.

Mortality

  • Studying mortality data can be easily viewed as analysis of time to event data.

  • The variable of interest is the life-span of an individual. We define \(X\) as the nonnegative and continuous random variable describing time from birth of an individual until death.

  • Three functions characterize and describe the distribution of \(X\):

    • the survival function, which is defined as the probability of an individual surviving beyond age x: \(S(x)=Pr(X>x)= \int_x^\infty f(t)dt\) ,

    • the probability density function: \(f(x)= -S'(x)\)

    • and the hazard rate (known as force of mortality in demography), it describes the instantaneous rate of death at age \(x\), given survival until \(x\): \(h(x)=\frac{f(x)}{S(x)}=\frac{d\ lnS(x)}{dx}\).

Death rates

  • To analyze mortality data, we have to make assumptions about the distribution of the random variable \(X\) and how it varies across individuals.

  • The simplest assumption is that all individuals in one birth-cohort live their lives according to the same life-span distribution, hence, ignoring other sources of heterogeneity.

  • The choice of the distribution is commonly based on the hazard rate.

  • The traditional assumption is that the hazard is constant over each one-year age-interval. It is, however, different between ages. This “piece-wise constant” assumption is the basis for the calculation of empirical death rates.

Death rates

  • In general at age \(i\), during year \(j\) we define as death rate the following ratio: \(m_{ij}=\frac{Y_{ij}}{E_{ij}}\)

  • where \(E_{ij}\) are the number of person-years aged \(i\) years during the year \(j\) and \(Y_{ij}\) are the number of deaths that occurred during the year \(j\) and attained age \(i\)

  • The assumption of a constant hazard over short time intervals implies that the total number of deaths over a specifed age- and year-interval, \(Y_{ij}\), is a Poisson distribution with mean: \(Y_{ij} \sim Poisson(m_{ij}*E_{ij})\)

  • (Poisson regression)

Models

We have two alternative way to estimate \(μ(x)\):

  1. let μ(x) free series of estimated death rates, (semi-parametric approach).

  2. force μ(x) to follow a certain functional form, parametric models:

Model \(\mu(x)=\)
Gompertz(1825) \(ae^{bx}\)
Makeham(1860) \(c+ae^{bx}\)
Logistic(1932) \(c+ \frac{ae^{bx}}{1+\alpha e^{bx}}\)
Weibull(1951) \(\frac{1}{\sigma}(\frac{x}{M})^{\frac{M}{\sigma} -1}\)
Heligman-Pollard(1980) \(A^{(x+b)^C} + De^{-E(\ln x- \ln F)^2}+GH^x\)

Gompertz

Gompertz Model

  • After almost 200 years, Benjamin Gompertz’ exponential formula remains the starting point for descriptions of the age trajectory of adult mortality rates in numerous species including our own.

  • But it is only a starting point.

  • Discoveries emerging from the measurement of hazard rates at advanced ages in large populations of model organisms as well as humans have now directed attention onto systematic deviations from Gompertz’ formula.

Density Function: \(f(X=x)=\alpha e^{\beta x}\exp[\frac{\alpha}{\beta}(1-e^{\beta x})]\)

Force of Mortality: \(\mu(x)=ae^{bx}\)

Simulating and fitting Gompertz data

  • Often it is useful to start with simulate data for understanding whether the estimation procedure is suitable and it does not contain bugs.

  • The random variable we will simulate is the total number of death counts within a Lexis square.

  • In order to use the Poisson framework, we need both the true hazard \(\mu(x)\) and a given exposure population \(E_x\) for each square (data available in the folder).

Simulating and fitting Gompertz data

  • Let us assume that we know the law that generated the true mortality rates (actually it is an unknown function).

  • Therefore we assume that the force of mortality is modeled by a Gompertz with parameters \(a =0.00001\) and \(b = 0.1\).

  • The slope parameter \(b\) of \(0.1\) is typical in human populations for adult ages from 30-85.

set.seed(2)
a <- 0.00001
b <- 0.1

ages <- expdata[,1]
E <- expdata[,2]
m <- length(ages)

mx.true <- a * exp(b * ages)

  • The random variable we will simulate is the total number of death counts.

  • Through Poisson simulation, let’s compute the age-at-death distribution by using the true rates for each age. The means of the Poisson are given in the vector \(\mu(x)true * E_x\)

mu<- mx.true * E
Y.sim <- rpois(m, lambda=mu)
plot(Y.sim)

  • The main advantage of using a Poisson setting is the sum of real deaths is equal to the sum of the estimated ones.
  • Starting from simulated Deaths count, let’s compute the simulated mortality rates. \(m_x(sim)= \frac{D_x(sim)}{E_x}\)
mx.sim <- Y.sim / E
plot(mx.sim)

  • Starting from Poisson Distribution assumption, It is usual to assume that the total number of deaths: \(Y_{x} \sim Poisson(\mu(x) E_x)\)

  • Given a series of ages and deaths counts, we can treat the total number of deaths as if Poisson variables, with the log-likelihood:

    • \(\ln L(\theta) \propto \sum_{i=1}^m \{ y_i\ln[\lambda_i(\theta)]- \lambda_i(\theta) \}\)
  • Where \(\theta\) are the parameters to estimate, \(\mu(x)= f(\theta,...,)\)

  • Given \(Y_x\) and \(E_x\) , we maximize:

    • \(\ln L(a,b|Y_x,E_x) \propto \sum_{x} \{ y_x\ln[ae^{bx} E_x]- ae^{bx} E_x \}\)

    • \(\propto \sum_{x} \{ y_x\ln[ae^{bx}]- ae^{bx} E_x \}\)

  • Make attention! We need to change the log-likelihood sign. The default optimization function in R minimizes the objective function while we need to maximize the log-likelihood.
lnLLKgom <- function(theta, ages, Y, E){
  # parameters
  a <- theta[1]
  b <- theta[2]
  # Gompertz mu
  mu <- a * exp(b * ages) 
  llk <- - sum(Y * log(mu) - mu*E)}
st.val <- c(a,b)
fit <- optim(par=st.val,
             fn=lnLLKgom,
             ages=ages, Y=Y.sim, E=E)
a.hat <- fit$par[1]
b.hat <- fit$par[2]

Standard Error

a.hat
## [1] 9.933422e-06
b.hat
## [1] 0.1001843

\(I(\theta)=-E \Big[\frac{\delta^2 \ln L(\theta)}{\delta\theta\delta\theta'}\Big] \approx H(\hat{\theta})\)

library(nlme)
Hessian <- fdHess(pars=fit$par, fun=lnLLKgom,
ages=ages, Y=Y.sim, E=E)$Hessian
vcmat <- solve(Hessian)
se.theta <- sqrt(diag(vcmat))

as.hat <- c(a.hat-2*se.theta[1], a.hat, a.hat+2*se.theta[1])
bs.hat <- c(b.hat-2*se.theta[2], b.hat, b.hat+2*se.theta[2])
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(rep(1,3), as.hat, cex=1.5,
ylab="a", xlab="", xaxt="n", pch=c(3,4,3))
points(1, a, col=2, pch=1, cex=1.5)
legend("topleft", c("Fitted", "95% CI", "True"),
col=c(1,1,2), pch=c(4,3,1), pt.cex=1.5)
plot(rep(1,3), bs.hat, cex=1.5,
ylab="b", xlab="", xaxt="n", pch=c(3,4,3))
points(1, b, col=2, pch=1, cex=1.5)

Models

Stochastic Models

Stochastic Models

  • Nowadays this latter approach represents the most widespread among scholars
  • Thanks to its advantages just like the possibility to obtain a mortality surface as output
  • One of the most used stochastic models is the Lee-Carter (1992)

Lee Carter Model

  • L. and C. using SVD, proposed a log-bilinear model for mortality rates incorporating both age and year effects:

    • \(ln(m_{ij})= \alpha_{i} +\beta_{i}\kappa_{j} +\epsilon_{ij}\)

    • \({\alpha_{i}}\) is the general shape of the log-mortality at age \(i\)

    • \({\kappa_{j}}\) represents the time trend index of general mortality level

    • \({\beta_{i}}\) indicates the sensitivity of the log-mortality at age \(i\) to variations in the time index

    • \({\epsilon_{ij}}\) is the residual term at age \(x\) and time \(t\).

  • With constraints:

    • \(\sum_{i}{\beta_{i}}^2 = 1;\ \sum_{j}k_j =0\)

  • In the traditional LC formulation, \(\kappa_t\) is usually modeled by an ARIMA(0,1,0):

    • \(\kappa_{t} = \kappa_{t-1} + \delta + \epsilon_t,\)
    • \(\quad \epsilon_t \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\kappa})\),
    • where \(\delta\) is the drift parameter and \(\epsilon_t\) are the error terms, normally distributed with null mean and variance \(\sigma^2_{\kappa}\).
  • ARIMA(p,d,q) Model
    • AR=AutoRegression and p is the order,
    • I=Integration, d is the order,
    • MA=Moving Average, q is the order.

  • So the ARIMA (p,d,q) is a ARMA(p,q) model on the differences of order “d” instead of on the real value.

Simulating and fitting

  • We would like to investigate the Lee-Carter model ability to estimate the real parameters (in the real case supposed unknowns)

  • Generation of \(m(x)\) true
One <- matrix(1, nrow=n, ncol=1)
MU.true <- exp(aT %*% t(One) + bT %*% t(kT))
D.true <- MU.true * EXP

  • Using Poisson assumption, we can simulate \(D_x\) and \(m(x)\).
  • We use the simulate \(m(x)\) in order to check model performance
D.sim <- matrix(NA, m, n)
for(i in 1:n){
D.sim[,i] <- rpois(m, lambda=D.true[,i])
}
MU.sim <- D.sim / EXP
## deaths
D <- D.sim
D[D==0] <- 1
## exposures
E <-EXP
E[E==0] <- 1
## log-rates
lMX <- log(D/E)
alpha.h <- apply(lMX, 1, mean)
## centering the log-death rates
cent.logMX <- sweep(lMX, 1, alpha.h)
## apply the SVD
SVD <- svd(cent.logMX)
## set and normalize beta and kappa
beta.h <- SVD$u[,1] / sum(SVD$u[,1])
kappa.h <- SVD$v[,1] * SVD$d[1] * sum(SVD$u[,1])

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(ages, alpha.h, t="o")
plot(ages, beta.h, t="o")
plot(years, kappa.h, t="o")

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

## fitted log-mortality

lMXhat <- alpha.h%*%t(One) + beta.h %*% t(kappa.h)

True Vs. Fitted

Model Checklist

  • Once a model has been developed and parameters have been estimated or calibrated, it is important to consider whether it is a good model or not. Guidelines by Cairns, Blake and Dowd (2008)

    • The model should be consistent with historical data.
    • Long-term dynamics under the model should be biologically reasonable.
    • Parameter estimates should be robust relative to the period of data and range of ages employed.
    • Model forecasts should be robust relative to the period of data and range of ages employed.
    • The model should be relatively parsimonious.

Oeppen and Vaupel 2002

  • Oeppen and Vaupel 2002 they show a remarkable linear trend in the female life expectancy (at birth, period basis), from 1840 to 2000.

  • Over this entire 160-year period, the record life expectancy consistently increased by 0.24 years of life per calendar year of time.

  • Key Message:… rate of 24 years per century

LCfit <- fit(lc(), Dxt = dx_italia, Ext = ex_italia, ages = age, years = yv)
plot(LCfit)
names(LCfit)
BIC(LCfit); AIC(LCfit)

plot(LCres, type = "colourmap", reslim = c(-3.5, 3.5))

# The period indexes are forecasted using a Multivariate Random Walk with Drift (MRWD). 
# The cohort index is forecasted using an ARIMA(p; d; q) . By default: ARIMA(1; 1; 0).
# h= number of years ahead to forecast
# level=  confidence level for prediction intervals of the period and cohort indices.
# jumpchoice option to select the jump-off rates, i.e. the rates from the final year of observation, to use in projections of mortality rates.  
# "fit"(default) uses the fitted rates and  "actual" uses the actual rates from the final year.
# kt.lookback optional argument to specify the look-back window to use in the estimation of the MRWD for period indexes. 
# By default all the estimated values are used in estimating the MRWD. If  kt.lookback is provided then the last  kt.lookback years of kt are used.
LCfor <- forecast(LCfit, h=50, level=95)    # proiezione 
names(LCfor)
LCfor$rates
plot(LCfor)
